<h3 id="so-how-should-we-structure-the-pitch">So how should we structure the pitch?</h3>

<p><img src="/assets/img/image7.png" alt="image" title="image" /> A good structure for a pitch is to
cover some basic areas to make sure that all the key information is
shared</p>

<ul>
  <li>High Concept</li>
  <li>Key Features</li>
  <li>Storyboards</li>
  <li>Business Case</li>
  <li>Pitch Summary</li>
  <li>Defensive Slides</li>
</ul>

<h4 id="how-long-should-it-be">How Long Should It Be?</h4>

<p><img src="/assets/img/image8.png" alt="image" title="image" /></p>

<p>Itâ€™s been scientifically proven that 10 minutes is the greatest amount
of time a person can concentrate before their mind starts to wander.</p>

<p>It may not sound very long but you may well find you struggle to
communicate everything you want in that time and youâ€™ll be constantly
trimming your presentation, finely tuning each word and image to make
sure you get theÂ most bang-for-buck.</p>

<p>I would say that you should be able to get across your High Concept in
less than 1 minute, leaving you 9 minutes to get across your features,
scenarios, business case and summary before questions.</p>

<h3 id="high-concept-styleclear-both">High Concept {style=â€clear: both;â€}</h3>

<p>The first element to share is your <strong>High Concept</strong>, what is the game
really all about?</p>

<p>It should be a compelling and unique idea that can be communicated in
just a couple of sentences. This is commonly known as the â€œElevator
Pitchâ€ with the idea being that you could jump in a lift on the ground
floor with the person youâ€™re presenting to and make your pitch memorable
before they leave on the 2nd floor.</p>

<p><a href="http://pashley.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/image9.png"><img src="/assets/img/image_thumb1.png" alt="image" title="image" /></a></p>

<p>This means that itâ€™s important that your <strong>high concept is easy to
communicate</strong>, memorable &amp; easy to pass on.</p>

<p>Once that person gets out of the elevator theyâ€™re going to tell someone
â€œWow! I just heard a great idea in the life, let me tell you about
itâ€¦â€</p>

<p>Remember this is a hook, itâ€™s a seed, itâ€™s the first contact with your
idea but it should be finely tuned and water-tight.</p>

<p>Preparing this short High Concept is a tough exercise but it really
focuses your attention and gets to the core of your game idea.</p>

<p>Thereâ€™s an even shorter form of High Concept thatâ€™s often called the
â€œ<strong>X Statement</strong>â€, this encapsulates the essence of your idea in just a
few words. Theyâ€™re not intended to tell someone everything about your
idea but just enough to get their appetite going.</p>

<p>Here are a few examples, you could probably guess the game from just the
statement, which is the idea.</p>

<div style="clear: both;">

![image](/assets/img/image10.png "image")

"Improve the Age of your Brain in just 10 minutes a day"

</div>

<div style="clear: both;">

![image](/assets/img/image11.png "image")

"Create virtual people and run their lives"

</div>

<h4 id="set-the-scene-styleclear-both">Set The Scene {style=â€clear: both;â€}</h4>

<p><img src="/assets/img/image12.png" alt="image" title="image" /></p>

<p>So, youâ€™ve nailed the <strong>High Concept</strong> and now itâ€™s time to give some
more detail so everyone understands exactly what our offering is. The
High Concept followed by this extra level of detail will frame the rest
of the presentation.</p>

<p>Youâ€™re aiming to go top-down, start high and drill in to more detail as
you go deeper into your presentation. This way the concept starts to
become clearer and clearer as you progress.</p>

<p>Adding in layers like this also ensures that everyone is expecting the
same thing, it would be awful if you got 1/2 way through your pitch and
someone said â€œOhh, I thought you were pitching a Racing Game but itâ€™s
actually a Farming Gameâ€</p>

<p>Cover the
basics: Who is the player in the game? What are they doing in the game? Why are they doing what theyâ€™re doing? Where is the game set? How do they do it? Whoâ€™s the audience? What platform is it on?</p>

<p>Remember, keep it high level, add in the layers later in your
presentation.</p>

<h3 id="key-features">Key Features</h3>

<p>Itâ€™s generally held that you only need 4 elements to a product before a
buyer will make their decision. No more, no less.</p>

<p>We have the <strong>High Concept</strong> so we only need <strong>3 Key Features</strong> to get
to a decision point. This means itâ€™s incredibly important that these few
things add up to something amazing and itâ€™s a lot of pressure to make
sure theyâ€™re complete and enticing but itâ€™s a tried &amp; tested formula.</p>

<p>The <strong>Key Features</strong> need to deliver on the promise set by the High
Concept, they need to expose unique and exciting elements of your game
experience.
Remember:</p>

<p><strong><span style="font-size: large;">We only want 3 Key Features</span></strong></p>

<p>Itâ€™s probably true that your game has loads of features but you have to
pick the 3 strongest features on which to hang your pitch.</p>

<h4 id="make-it-visual">Make It Visual</h4>

<p>By far the best way to communicate your <strong>High Concept</strong> and <strong>3 Key
Features</strong> is to use visuals in whatever format you choose.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/img/image49.png" alt="image" title="image" /></p>

<p>Letâ€™s use one of my favourite games, Burnout Paradise (the only PS3
Platinum I have), as an example of how this may work by using some stock
